@rolfbjarne Do you have a hunch as to what could be the issue? I would like to help push this ticket along. 

Could it be a change in GC behaviour and perhaps suppressing GC until the loop is done could help, if possible? (As a workaround)

AFAIK the serialisation all happens in managed code, so I am wondering why only Apple OSs are affected.

@BrzVlad to add to this, I have recently spent time working on a workaround. 

Looking at a dotnet-trace, the majority of time is spend creating a new XML writer. 

Combined with this, and GC looking like the culprit, I tried to change the code to reuse the XML writer, which required me to use a reader to write the nodes and then flush the XML writer after every serialization. Here is an excerpt from that workaround:

```
var result = new List<string>();

using (var stringWriter = new StringWriter())
{
	var settings = new XmlWriterSettings { CheckCharacters = false, ConformanceLevel = ConformanceLevel.Fragment };

	using (var xmlWriter = XmlWriter.Create(stringWriter, settings))
	{
		foreach (var item in itemsToSerialize)
		{
			stringWriter.GetStringBuilder().Clear();

			var xe = item;
			using (var reader = xe.CreateReader())
			{
				xmlWriter.WriteNode(reader, false);
				xmlWriter.Flush();
			}

			result.Add(stringWriter.ToString());
		}
	}
}

return result;
```

Although doing this I was able to almost achieve comparable performance, however I still see more jitters than before .NET 9.
